  "text": "DNase I catalyzes the endonucleolytic hydrolysis of double-stranded DNA with a low, but not completely random, selectivity (Lomonossoff et al., 1981; [CITATION_1] Travers, 1984, 1985) . The hydrolysis patterns which result Fig. 1 . DNase I-DNA structure. This structure contains the protein bound to a nicked quasi-continuous double helix of 14 base pairs which shows the locations of the major and the minor grooves of the DNA relative to the protein [CITATION_2] Suck et al., 1998) . The protein backbone is shown in black and the two DNA strands in green and cyan. The sidechain atoms of Arg41 (magenta) and Tyr76 (yellow), which bind to DNA in the minor groove and completely fill this groove, have been space-filled and highlighted. The positions of Ser138 (red) and Ser174 (blue) are indicated by representing their sidechain atoms in the space-filling mode. These two amino acids, which do not interact with the DNA, are located on the surface of DNase I in proximity to the DNA major groove.",
